The '''American Artists Professional League''' ('''AAPL''') is an American organization that promotes artists and their works.<ref>[http://www.in.gov/library/4224.htm American Artists Professional League Scrapbooks.] Indiana.gov. Retrieved February 10, 2014.</ref> It was formed in 1928 in [[New York City]] by [[Frederick Ballard Williams]], and the first meeting was held at the [[Salmagundi Club|Salmagundi Art Club]] on January 29, 1928. Ballard became the organization's national chairman.<ref>[http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/american-artists-professional-league-records-5629 American Artists Professional League records, 1928-1980]. Archives of American Art. Retrieved February 10, 2014.</ref><ref>David Bernard Dearinger. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=PHH45aYubp4C&pg=PA589 Paintings and Sculpture in the Collection of the National Academy of Design: 1826-1925]''. Hudson Hills; 2004. {{ISBN|978-1-55595-029-3}}. p. 589.</ref> The organization has hosted an annual Grand National Exhibition for 83 years to promote artists specializing in realistic art forms.
