The '''Symphony No. 72''' in [[D major]] (Hoboken 1/72) is a [[symphony]] by [[Joseph Haydn]].  The symphony was probably composed between [[1763 in music|1763]] and [[1765 in music|1765]].  The date of this composition is earlier than its number suggests. This work is not well chronologically placed in the Hoboken numbering system: it was composed fifteen to twenty years before the neighboring works.

==Instrumentation==
It is scored for [[flute]], two [[oboe]]s, [[bassoon]], four [[Horn (instrument)|horns]] and [[String section|strings]]. It is one of the few [[Classical period (music)|classical-era]] symphonies to include four horns rather than two.  This work is closely related to the [[Symphony No. 31 (Haydn)|Hornsignal Symphony]] because of its many soloistic horn passages<ref name="oxford-jones">Oxford Composer Companions: Haydn, ed. David Wyn Jones, Oxford University Press, 2002. {{ISBN|0-19-866216-5}}</ref> and is also related to the "Day Trilogy" symphonies [[Symphony No. 6 (Haydn)|6]], [[Symphony No. 7 (Haydn)|7]] and [[Symphony No. 8 (Haydn)|8]] because of the concertante passages for other instruments.<ref name="apbrown">Brown, A. Peter, ''The Symphonic Repertoire'' (Volume 2). Indiana University Press ({{ISBN|025333487X}}), pp. 84-86 (2002).</ref>

==Movements==
#[[Tempo#Italian_tempo_markings|Allegro]]
#[[Tempo#Italian_tempo_markings|Andante]], {{music|time|6|8}}
#[[Minuet|Menuet]] & Trio, {{music|time|3|4}}
#Finale: [[Tempo#Italian_tempo_markings|Andante]] (Thema. Var. I–VI), {{music|time|2|4}} — [[Tempo#Italian_tempo_markings|Presto]], {{music|time|6|8}}

The horns are silent in the second movement.  In their place are solo passages for flute and violin.<ref name="hcrl-chronicle-v1">HC Robbins Landon, ''Haydn: Chronicle and Works'', 5 vols, (Bloomington and London: Indiana University Press, 1976– ) v. 1, ''Haydn: the Early Years, 1732–1765''</ref>

The minuet begins and ends with the same phrase ''piano'' with the ending as an echo.  The strings are silent in the trio which is scored for all the winds minus the flute.<ref name="apbrown"/>

The finale is a set of marching variations that features many soloists accompanied by strings.  The first variation features solo flute, the second a solo cello, the third a solo violin and the fourth a solo [[violone]].  The fifth variation is scored for oboe, two horns and strings while the sixth variation is for flute, oboe, bassoon, four horns and strings.  The movement concludes with a Presto [[coda (music)|coda]] in {{music|time|6|8}} and featuring a final horn flourish.<ref name="hcrl-chronicle-v1"/>

